1 (d) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, the supervisor shall
2 maintain information from a soil conservation and water quality plan in a manner that
3 protects the identity of the person for whom the plan is prepared.
4 (2) The supervisor shall make a soil conservation and water quality plan
5 available to:
6 (i) The Department of the Environment for enforcement action
7 under § 4–413 of the Environment Article; and
8 (ii) The Department, [which may use the information for statistical
9 purposes] FOR:
10 1. ENFORCEMENT ACTION UNDER SUBTITLE 8 OF THIS
11 TITLE; AND
12 2. STATISTICAL PURPOSES.
13 (3) The Department shall:
14 (i) Maintain the information in the manner that protects the
15 identity of the person for whom the plan is prepared; and
16 (ii) Make any information from a plan available to the Department
17 of the Environment to support the development of a compliance or enforcement case for
18 purposes of addressing an existing water quality problem in accordance with procedures
19 established between the departments and the State Soil Conservation Committee.
20 (e) As a condition to extending any benefit of this title to any land not owned or
21 controlled by the State or any of its agencies, or to performing work on them, the
22 supervisors may require contributions in money, services, materials, or otherwise to any
23 operations conferring benefits, and may require the land occupier to enter into and perform
24 agreements or covenants concerning the permanent use of the land as tends to prevent or
25 control erosion.
26 (f) The supervisors of two or more districts may cooperate with one another in
27 the exercise of any powers conferred by this title.
28 (g) No provision relating to acquisition, operation, or disposition of property by
29 other public bodies is applicable to a district, unless the provision specifically so states.
30 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
31 October 1, 2025.

